the worlds top warblers are puckering 
up for tunes ranging from tchaikovsky to led zeppelin at the 11th 
annual international whistleoff this weekend 
i dont want to sound boastful but i think its a godgiven 
gift said contestant patty ediger of dayton ore i think 
maybe the shape of a persons mouth and his teeth have something to 
do with it she practices two to three hours a day in the 
months preceding the whistleoff i go up to the wee hours of the 
morning she said it takes a lot of time if you want to be 
good 
whistling as an art ranks very high in comparison with other 
musical arts said chamber of commerce spokeswoman jean stokke 
these are serious musicians and theyre very competitive 
thirty people were competing in four divisions today and sunday 
in what is billed as the nations premier whistling event 
whistlers from 15 states canada and mexico compete for a 
roundtrip flight to mexico or the caribbean the prize will go to 
the events grand champion with trophies going to the top three in 
each division 
among the whistlers are former threetime grand champion roy 
thoreson of calgary alberta and former twotime grand champion 
nancy foran of yakima wash 
other contestants include michael sherman of san jose calif 
