<TEXT>
the federal budget deficit climbed by 229 
billion last month after posting a rare surplus in june the 
treasury department said 
the new batch of red ink brought the deficit for the first 10 
months of the fiscal year that began oct 1 to 1420 billion only 
slightly less than the amount for the same period last year 
government ledger books were in the black with a 93 billion 
surplus for june mainly as a result of quarterly tax payments by 
businesses and individuals 
but the reagan administration is projecting the deficit for the 
fiscal year that ends sept 30 at 1523 billion that is above the 
administrations 1467 billion deficit estimate in february but 
below the 157 billion forecast by the congressional budget office 
at the beginning of the year 
the cbo revised its figures friday however to project a 155 
billion deficit james l blum acting director of the 
congressional agency said stronger economic growth than expected 
for the first half was responsible 
the cbo is not expecting acrosstheboard spending cuts to be 
triggered this month by a law calling for a balanced budget by 
1993 blum said 
he said cbo projections indicate there is no way the budget 
could be balanced by 1993 in the absence of further policy changes 
such as spending cuts or tax increases the agency in fact 
projects a 121 billion deficit in 1993 if present policies are 
unchanged 
surprising economic growth which has boosted government 
revenues and lowered government spending for such programs as 
unemployment benefits has been credited with reducing the deficit 
this year 
many economists believe the deficit will rise again in the 
fiscal year beginning oct 1 the administration however 
predicts it will drop to 1401 billion in 1989 when figured 
according to guidelines contained in the grammrudman deficit 
reduction law 
last months deficit was 27 percent higher than the imbalance 
in july a year ago 
government spending in july actually dropped 69 percent when 
compared to june spending fell to 836 billion but tax receipts 
dropped even more sharply falling by 388 percent to 607 billion 
tax receipts for the first 10 months of the fiscal year were up 
57 percent to 7417 billion while spending is up 46 percent to 
8837 billion 
as usual the largest spending categories were the military 
social security and other programs in the department of health and 
human services and interest on the national debt 
military spending totaled 239 billion in july and 2371 
billion in the first 10 months of this fiscal year up 33 percent 
from the same period last year 
social security payments totaled 172 billion in july and 178 
billion so far this budget year an increase of 58 percent 
spending for other hhs programs amounted to 120 billion last 
month and 1308 billion this budget year up 33 percent 
interest payments on the 26 trillion national debt cost 145 
billion in july and 1836 billion so far this year 
