<DOCNO> AP880820-0018 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
scientists in taiwan say a new material shows 
possible superconductivity at up to 66 degrees above the current 
record temperature but other scientists have reacted with caution 
the new report does not include a crucial test for proving 
superconductivity so the material should be considered only a 
possible superconductor the other experts said 
superconductivity is the ability of some materials to conduct 
electricity without loss to resistance if the materials can be 
made practical they may lead to such advances as smaller more 
powerful computers and magnetically levitated highspeed trains 
materials created so far must be chilled before they will 
superconduct researchers are trying to develop materials with as 
high a superconducting temperature as possible to minimize the 
expense of cooling and so make superconductors more practical 
the new report from taiwan says five samples of the material 
showed no electrical resistance at temperatures above minus 208 
degrees fahrenheit one sample showed no resistance at minus 168 
degrees the researchers said 
the current widely accepted record is minus 234 degrees 
the new research is disclosed in high tc update a 
newsletter published by the ames laboratory at iowa state 
university under contract to the us department of energy tc 
refers to the temperature at which a material begins to 
superconduct 
the newsletter obtained a copy of a paper by researchers at the 
industrial technology research institute and the national tsing hua 
university both in hsinchu taiwan 
the researchers reported their material includes the same 
ingredients as the current recordholding compound thallium 
calcium barium copper and oxygen 
some samples that conducted electricity without resistance at 
temperatures above minus 208 degrees eventually lost that ability 
others that could do so above minus 226 degrees still had that 
ability after a week the researchers said 
the reason for the changes in performance in some samples has 
not yet been pinpointed they said 
superconductivity researcher paul chu of the university of 
houston said he found no errors in the reported resistance 
measurements when he visited the researchers recently in taiwan 
but he also said he knew of no measurements of the magnetic 
characteristics of the new material superconducting materials give 
off a characteristic magnetic signal when exposed to a magnetic 
field and existence of this signal is considered a crucial test of 
whether a material is a true superconductor 
without a report of that measurement the material should be 
considered only a possible superconductor he said 
similarly physicist john clem at the ames laboratory said the 
manuscript from the taiwan researchers is very convincing but 
that the lack of magnetic measurements is disturbing 
clem said he wouldnt get excited about the new material 
until such measurements are reported and the experimental results 
are duplicated by other researchers 
</TEXT>
