<TEXT>
four andean condors that will serve as scouts 
for reintroduction of the gravely threatened california condor into 
the wild are headed for temporary pens in a rugged mountain range 
the 3 and 4monthold avian pioneers hatched and reared in 
zoos will spend several weeks in mesh enclosures as scientists 
prepare them for their first flights over the dry mountains and 
foothills that once supported a thriving population of california 
condors 
the california species a black vulturelike carrion eater 
with a wingspan up to 9 feet has dwindled to a mere 28 all in 
captivity 
two andean condors from the san diego wild animal park were 
loaded into airlinestyle animal shipping crates friday evening for 
a 200mile trip to the secret holding pens in the los padres 
national forest 75 miles northeast of los angeles tom hanscom a 
spokesman for the animal park said in a telephone interview friday 
they want to arrive and put the birds in their new home in the 
dark of night so the birds awaken the next morning thinking they 
are in the same place they were before hanscom said as his crew 
was ready to depart at 645 pm for the sixhour drive 
the birds were not drugged but were captured and wrapped in 
blankets by familiar handlers he said 
by moving them in the dark it basically minimizes the 
stress hanscom said 
a third andean condor hatched at the los angeles zoo will join 
the contingent along with a fourth flown in from a us fish and 
wildlife service center in patuxent md said michael wallace the 
los angeles zoo biologist overseeing the program 
the andean birds all females to prevent breeding in the wild 
will be used to test techniques biologists hope to use perhaps as 
soon as 1992 to begin returning the california condor to nature 
more andean condors will be added to the test flock later 
in a 440000 program overseen by the us fish and wildlife 
service the birds will be taken to a special mesh enclosure 
measuring about 20 feet by 40 feet and 15 feet high in rugged 
territory the exact spot is secret to deter the curious or the 
malicious 
about november when the birds are able to fly they will be 
fitted with radio monitoring gear and released its expected they 
will cover much of the california condors fivecounty range a 
land of bare grassy hills dotted with occasional oaks and rugged 
rocky cliffs and canyons in the mountains that ring the southern 
end of the san joaquin valley 
the purpose of the test hanscom said is twofold to see how 
birds hatched in captivity adapt to freedom and to see if such 
birds can learn to fend for themselves in a region without native 
birds of their species to serve as examples 
the program also will help scientists spot such possible hazards 
as poison bait illegally left for coyotes or lead shot in animal 
carcasses left by hunters hanscom said 
the andean birds will be captured from the wild when its time 
to release their california cousins hanscom said the first 
california birds could be released as early as 1992 if breeding 
programs are successful he said 
the andean condor was chosen for the experiment because it is 
the closest living relative to the california condor though the 
andean species is endangered they number in the thousands 
the california condor north americas largest land bird once 
roamed widely along the west coast but its numbers had shrunk to 
40 when the fish and wildlife service launched a rescue effort in 
1976 
