<TEXT>
a daylabor firm will be fined 60000 for 
violating the new federal immigration law a reduced fine that 
still is the largest ever levied for such violations federal 
immigration officials said 
the us immigration and naturalization service initially fined 
readymen a company that provides temporary help to construction 
firms and factories 308000 for hiring five illegal immigrants 
and committing more than 515 violations in recordkeeping 
after two months of negotiations however the two sides agreed 
on the smaller fine 
its not our intention to put anyone out of business ad 
moyer the chicago ins director said friday the moment that im 
assured that they are doing everything they can to comply with the 
law then im satisfied 
he said the company was now on the right track and that the 
settlement demonstrates the effectiveness of the law 
readyman president james heraty said he felt the sanction was 
fair and that his company would try to be a model company in 
the industry 
heraty did acknowledge that the new law makes his business more 
difficult and that he occasionally has trouble finding enough 
workers 
i have never found so many people who dont have the id they 
need to get hired he said at a news conference 
the immigration law passed by congress in 1986 initially allowed 
some illegal aliens to seek amnesty and apply for legal residency 
in the united states the yearlong amnesty ended in may 
the second phase of the law begun in june 1987 makes employers 
responsible for verifying that their workers are legal residents 
and provides for fines if companies knowingly hire illegal aliens 
before the law employers faced no sanctions for hiring illegal 
aliens 
