<TEXT>
south and north korean delegates ended a 
second day of talks saturday but failed to make major progress on 
clearing the way for fullscale talks on a nonaggression pact and 
sharing the olympic games 
they agreed to a third meeting monday 
the two sides appeared far apart on all main issues as lawmakers 
from each side met in the south korean pavilion at the truce site 
straddling the demilitarized zone separating the two koreas on 
friday delegates met in the north korean pavilion 
the fivemember delegations shook hands and cracked jokes before 
beginning negotiations but observers described the mood as guarded 
chief south korean delegate park joonkyu in an opening speech 
offered a number of minor concessions on the terms for holding 
joint parliamentary talks the changes were basically rewordings of 
proposals and the south did not revise its main positions 
north koreas delegates said the south was making discussions 
more complex without making progress 
there is nothing new in your proposal said chief north 
korean delegate chon kum chol 
the north korean delegation continued to press for fullscale 
parliamentary talks on a nonaggression pact and allowing the north 
to cohost the olympic games that begin sept 17 in seoul 
south korea showed no willingness to back down on its position 
that the only solution for the olympics was for the north to 
participate in the games in seoul but that cohosting was 
impossible 
the meeting on friday also ended with no progress before the 
sides met park said he was optimistic an agreement could be 
negotiated but after the working meeting he rated chances for 
holding full talks at 5050 
park said he needs a little bit of glasnost using soviet 
leader mikhail s gorbachevs catchword for openness from north 
korea before agreeing to full talks on easing their 40year rivalry 
the korean peninsula was divided north and south at the end of 
world war ii in 1945 the nations technically are still at war 
since no peace treaty was signed after the korean war of 195053 
north korean has called for a joint meeting of the two 
countries parliaments involving nearly 1000 lawmakers to 
discuss the olympics and a nonaggression pact 
south korea sought to call a representative meeting of 20 
lawmakers from each side whose main business would be to fix the 
agenda and work out other details for full talks 
the north koreans also proposed that both legislatures make a 
joint declaration of nonaggression bypassing their governments 
seoul maintains that military matters must be handled by the 
executive branches of the two governments park said the north 
koreans are trying to avoid dealing with president roh taewoo and 
get 42000 us troops withdrawn from south korea 
chief north korean delegate chon kum chol reinterated his 
countrys demand to share in the olympics he said the event is 
not a simple sports game but a serious political problem which will 
decide the destiny of the korean people 
park said the only solution was for north korea to participate 
in the games he said south korea would keep the door open for 
north koreas participation but noted the deadline for entries is 
sept 2 
north korea is demanding to be a ohost at the olympics to stave 
